1 959

Meeting of the Gas Co directors this morning to approve the best bid for the 15 million debenture issue. Telephone conference with San Francisco at 8:30.

On the San Diego Union panel at the Rotary Club this noon on What's Coming for San Diego in the new year. My part financial conditions and growth.

This afternoon made a start on organizing the considerable amount of data I have gathered on the Soviet Economic Threat scheduled for Rotary next Thursday.

1959

Worked all day on the Rotary talk and made progress. All points are now available on uniform slips.

Phil called this noon. Had a chat on Life Insurance and Solar developments.

Jay Savage of U.S.C called this afternoon with two of his students Arnold G. Kluge and David B. Wake. Kluge is principally interested in Dipsosaurus. He made a list of my material and will request specimens later.

Went to Eleanor and Rod's for a family spread in the evening.

1 959

Flat tire this morning in a brand new casing; delayed my getting downtown.

At the office the rest of the morning. Worked over my speech on the Soviet Industrial Menace. Delivered it at the Rotary Club at noon. Seemed to go over OK. Had plenty of time; even had to stretch it a little.

Man called in the afternoon from Anchor-Hocking glass company. Told him I was in search of 96 mm amerseal caps. Changes of getting any seem slim.

Went to the Gray's for dinner tonight.

1 959

Citizens Advisory Committee Air Pollution Control District, met this morning 9-12.

At the office this afternoon 1-3. Long discussion with Hayden Ames concerning (1) smog situation in Los Angeles, and (2) on the Williams-PG&E damage suit.

Meeting of the Zoo board tonight. Voted to sell the Clark home on Point Loma for $85,000. I was against this; seems a little low to me.

He told me of a 17'2" whale caught for Marine Land early this week.

1 959

At the office this morning.

Talked social security and other matters with Bert Lynch.

Meeting of Company directors this noon until 2:30.

Went to Natural History Museum and got a number of specimens of which loans had been requested by a number of correspondents.

Tonight went to a dinner meeting of the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers and gave them a smog talk. It was a dinner meeting and then a rather long and boring business meeting. I finally got started at 8:40 and talked until 9:42--too long. Then about 10 minutes of questions. It went ok, but the the last part must be shortened. There were about 32 present including Jack Gregg of the Tribune.

What a wast of time!

1959

At the office this morning.
This afternoon drove to Fontana with Dr. J.B. Askew. We started at 4:20 and arrived at the Kaiser Steel Mill at 6:20.
The rest of our gang had previously arrived but had gone to some adjacent inn for drinks. We finally sate down to eat at the company cafeteria at about 7. Had a fine steak dinner.
The next event scheduled was a 17 minute movie explaining the plant but the projector wouldn't work so this was passed up.
After a few minutes devoted to So. Calif. Air Pollution Council business we adjourned for a guided tour of the steel plant. This was at 8.
The tour was exceedingly interesting and made the trip worthwhile, although a little strenuous for me. It recalled our Pittsburgh Saturday plant excursions of 50 years ago.
The plant is a completely integrated one having an annual capacity of 3 million tons of steel. There are 4
(Continued on April 28)

1959

Went out to State College at 8:30. Attended opening sessions of ASIH society, then heard Jay Savage's paper on the origin of the herpetofauna of Lower Calif.. Saw many friends, some not present last night. Had discussions with Ray Cowles and Dr. Findlay E. Russell.

Went down to the office in the afternoon. Did not go out to State College sessions, too tired as too much to do at home getting ready for the evening party for the board of governors of the I&H Society.

They began to arrive at about 5:50. Had cocktails and sat down to eat a little after 7. There was a total of about 85 present; this accurate to within 1 or 2. They left at 8:30 for the Natural history Museum where the governors had their annual meeting. As a past president, I am a member of the board. I went over to the meeting which began at 8:45. I stayed until 11 then went home very tired. Did some cleaning up; then to bed.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/07/2014 10:47 PM
  • pamg 03/07/2014 10:28 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:02 PM

1 959

This morning I got out at State College at 9:30. Missed the first paper on the Chichauhuan Desert by Milstead, but heard Woodbury on snake Dens, Bogert on Thermoregulation, and Norris on Adaptations in Desert Reptiles. All were good papers as of interest to me. During the Woodbury paper I sat next to Ross Hardy, who expressed the opinion that both decolor and concolor are valid subspecies. Woodbury, in his talk, remarked that the mountain rattlers of Utah are sufficiently different from lutosus to be recognized as a separate subspecies concolor - nuntuis intergrades were shown.

Went to lunch down in Mission Valley with Stebbins and his wife, just back from Africa and Cowles.

Returned to the meetings but was so tired that I came home at 3:30.

Still worn out from last night's entertainment, but at least the house has been straightened out again.

(June 23, continued)

Air Pollution Control Council. As usual everything was late; we started to eat at 8 - and the meeting started at 9. Got into several wrangles, but made a few worth-while decisions. Askew had come up from San Diego, but had to leave early. As a result of this meeting it is to be hoped that future meetings may be better organized and more efficient.

The session closed at 10:30.

1 959

Took the 8:30 train to Los Angeles to attend the convention of the Air pollution Control Association. Put up at the Statler which was the headquarters. Missed the morning general session through not having noticed it on the program. Saw Dr. Royal Sorenson of Cal. Tech., who said it was a good preliminary summary, but not outstanding.

Lunched at the Terrance Room; then went out and did a little shopping.

At 1:30 went to the session on the health aspects of air pollution. This lasted until 3:40. Saw Al Bush of UCLA there, but few others that I knew. The papers were interesting but the data came too fast to permit extensive notes. Got very sleepy toward the last. Then went to my room and rested.

Went to the Public Library from 6 to 8 and looked up several items necessary for the pink snake story. Then to the Biltmore Coffee Shop for dinner. This proved too long a walk for comfort.

1 959

Went to the first two papers in the automotive section at 9 AM. One was a substitute paper on controlling evaporative looses; the second was too technical to be of any interest to me, and the outlook for the others in the series was equally poor, so I left. Met Minardi, the only man in my Stanford class who owned and drove an automobile.

At 10:20 went over to the Public Library and started on the LA Examiner again Finally located the pink snake story article in the Nov. 25, 1923 issue. Am glad that long search is ended. Also cleaned up all the Ditmers books in the library.

Had considerable buzzing and feeling of pressure in my ears, with some reduction in my sense of hearing; so ate a light lunch and returned to the hotel for a rest. Had slept poorly the night before met Bob Brown, and old KW employe on the way back to the hotel.

Rested all afternoon. Ear trouble stopped after about 4 hours. Went down for supper; then to the newspaper shop at 5th & Hall for an NY Times. Feeling OK again.

1959

Ed called this morning and we had a chat.

Spent this morning preparing repots for our local smog committee; one on the APCA convention, the other on the meeting of the Southern California Coordinating Council.

Went to the general luncheon of the convention this noon. The speeches were a little on the dull and pretentions side but the meal was firly good. I sat with Al Bush and Jack Gregg.

Then went to the combustion session, at which 5 papers were presented. Chadwick of the Edison Co presided. They were scheduled to start at 2:30, but the room wasn't cleaned until 3:10, and then the microphone wouldn't work.

Chadwick thanked me for the smog paper I had sent him; he said it was the clearest compendium on the subject that he had seen.

I listed to the 5 papers; I wasn't interested in all of them but stayed anyway. There was no time for discussion which was too bad.

June 25, continued.

The oil refineries in Los Angeles County use more fuel than all the steam-electric generator plants. The hydrocarbons in the seam-electric plant stack gases are not high enough to be measured.

Saturday 27 June

Worked all day catching up with reading etc. Made good progress.

Went down to the office in the late afternoon and picked up the mail.

Rita Carroll wrote me that the Press had decided not to run an additional 1000 copies of Rattlesnakes at this time. They had considered doing this and had held the linotype slugs (about 6 tons) ever since Nov. 1956. Now they had received guotes and samples of a special. Kind of off-set job from some Eastern firm and have decided to use this method if an additional run should ever be necessary. This will save a possible unnecessary expenditures of $10,000 and is quite evidently a sound decision. I regret not being able to correct the typographical errors of which there are about 50 but otherwise I am not displeased by the decision.

Today I received a copy of the Desert Magazine with Charles Sheltons write-up about me. It is quite satisfactory.

______________________________________________
August 31, Continued

We had expected to go over to Berkley on Tuesday, so this upset our plans. I went down the main office of the Bank of America to learn what my credit card would allow. Found it was good for $100 checks, but there would be no difficulty in getting an OK for larger sums via their direct wire to SD. Not knowing how much I would need, I didn't get the money then. (Later I got what I needed by cashing a number of $100 checks at different branches.)

Went out to Fillmore St and ate at a sandwich joint. Then to the Stanford Medical Library. Worked there from 12:45 to 2:30. There was little that could be done as they were busy moving.

Date: Sunday, August 30, 1959

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/08/2014 06:16 PM

1 959

This morning early I called the Cadillac Agency and described my transmission trouble. They said bring it around and they would see how it drove so they could diagnose the trouble. I went down and was driven around by a mechanic named Westwood He drove up and down steep hills and everything went fine - no shift trouble. He said "I think its Ok, but maybe to play safe we should open it up and have a look. So I left it at the agency and fortunately gave him my Town House phone number. Soon he called up (I was un the shower, of course) and said the found the transmission badly shot. Labor cost would be $78.00 and material anything between $50 and $400. Would be unsafe to drive; might give out on the road at any time. Also after considerable mumbling he came out with the fact that they didn't accept out-of-town checks. After a lot of palaver I told him to go ahead, the car to be ready Wednesday night.

(Continued on Aug. 26)

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/08/2014 06:22 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:02 PM

1 959

Lots of telephoning this morning: to Harold Osmer about a prospective loan of his Mercury car that he never used during the week; to the Cadillac agency to learn about progress and to GG's friends in Berkeley. Finally reached Westwood at the Agency after several tries. He said the transmission was not so bad as they had first thought and the repairs would probably not reach $300. Still promised for Wednesday between 3 and 4 So we went down to Osmer's garage on Post St, picked up his car and drove over to Berkeley. Tried for mail; no soap. LeftGG with the car. Made a reservation for Wednesday night at the Silva Motel. Met Rita Carroll on the street; also Taylor] of the State Board of Health. Then went around to the University Press and talked over publish matters with Rita from 1 to 2:10. Then to MVZ but Stebbins wasn't in. Then up to the Library; the climb up the hill was quite a shore. Renewed my library card but was too tired to

1959

I phoned the Cad agency this morning and was told the car was ready. Using Harold Osmer's Mercury drove out Chestnut Street and cashed another $100 check. Loaded up our gear at the motel and found the missing brief case under one of the beds. Went down to the Cad agency and transferred the baggage to the Cad. Paid the bill; $270.83. Back to the Motel at 9:15.

1 959

Parked the car and left Silva at 945. Went to MVZ and talked over herpetological problems with Stebbins from 10:10 to 12:10. A very interesting session about his pineal eye project, Africa, and other matters. Went to lunch at the Shattuck; then waited for GG at the post office from 1:30 to 2:30. Got quite nervous. Finally called her at Nell's. Her watch was stopped. Still no mail.

Left for Sacramento at 2:45 and arrived at 4:25. The freeway is finished to the second Carquinez bridge, which was also in use. This made it an easy trip. Only 78 miles.

Called up Paul R. Watson, Jr. and found that Paul Sr, once my roommate at Stanford, had died 2-1/2 years ago. Had supper at the hotel and then went for a walk. It was nice and cool. Met Supervisor D. Austin.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/09/2014 10:13 PM

1 959

Went to the meeting of the directors of the State Chamber of Commerce this morning at 10. A fairly good meeting. Then to the regular luncheon. Sat next to Norman Sutherland and talked PG and E Developments

The luncheon talk was made by Herbert Hoover, Jr., on financial integrity.

After lunch had a talk with Dr. Arnold Beckman about Air Pollution Control problems. He thought that money might be raised to give Solar an RID contract to develop an afterburner placed next to the auto engine so that no heat exchange would be necessary. He also thought more of Hartley's Union Oil scheme than I do, using only an electric fuel pump and a 3-way valve.

GG went shopping for presents for the kids. I went back to the room and rested for the remainder of the afternoon.

Had dinner at the Senator Hotel; then sat on a bench in the State Capital grounds in cool of the evening

1 959

This morning went to the Sacramento Host Breakfast. This was the 33rd. Went in at 7:45. Breakfast was finished at 8:35; then introductions of guests took until 9:10. There were talks by McQuin president of the state fair; Valenine president of the State C of C; [{Clark Kerr]] president of U.C., and Governor Pat Brown. None of the talks were wroth writing home about.

We finally got out at 10:20 and then answered the usual scramble to pay the hotel bill, get the car out of the garage and load the baggage. We got under way at 11:00 and then got caught in a bad traffic jam near the State Fair Stopped at Lodi at 12:15 to change clothes and rearrange the baggage.

Had some lunch at Modesto. Arrived at Lancaster at 1 PM and ate at a drive-in. Then to the new Caravan Motel where we got a very glossy room for $12. Turned in at 8.

Miles today 370.

1 959

At the office this morning.

Asst City Manager Ed Blom called this noon and showed me stereopticon pictures he had taken at Rincon of a king snake (ringed) eating a gopher snake of substantially the same size. This was not a staged affair but a natural episode in the wild. I was surprised that the king snake should tackle so large a gopher snake. The king snake became frightened and took off with the tail of the gopher still protruding from its mouth.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/10/2014 12:35 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:02 PM

1 959

Drove up to los Angeles this morning; started at 9:30 and arrived at 12. Spent quite a bit of time looking over motels, as the Aster, although conveniently located, has become to poor to consider. Finally selected the Parkway at 1212 S. Alvarado (DV5-3988). It proved highly satisfactory although requiring auto transportation to the Shrine Auditorium.

Spent the afternoon reading and resting.

In the evening went to a performance of Airadne Auf Naxos by R. Strauss and enjoyed it. The principle were Eileen Farrell, Richard Lewis, Robert Symonds, Sena Jurinao, and Rita Streich. Rita was not quite up to her part.

This had been preceded by Danses Concertantes by Stravinsky. It was entertaining but nothing to write home about.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/10/2014 12:44 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:02 PM

1959

Visited with Ed this morning from 12:40 to 3:15 and discussed his affairs and family matters at great length.

In the evening went to a very satisfactory performance of Pagliacci with Mario Del Monaco, Dolores Mari, Robert Weede, Cesare Curzi, and Theodor Uppman.

This was followed by a most impressive performance of Carmina Burana which we both enjoyed greatly; music, dancing, scenery, and costumes were excellent. Altogether it was an outstanding evening.

1 959

Went to Los Angeles today to attend a meeting of the directors of the Calif. State Chamber of Commerce.

This was a hard luck trip. Went down to catch the train leaving at 6:30, but there had been a freight wreck just north of Capistrano at midnight last night -- two freight trains met head on.

We waited until 7:20 for a bus to be supplied. This took us as far north as Santa Ana where we were transferred to a train. We reached Santa Ana at 9:15 but the train didn't leave until 10. It would have saved time if the bus had kept on going to LA. Arrived at LA at 10:50 and at the meeting (called for 10 AM) at 11:10. Went to the meeting and then to lunch. Missed Pres. Hotchkis with whom I wanted to take about Founders, but did talk to a couple of other directors. Called Ed instead of going out to see him as I knew the train would run behind schedule.

Left LA at 2:30 and arrived at [{SD]] at 7:15. A slow tiresome trip.
